Very nice dispenser, but a little slow
October 29, 2011
I got this on sale and it is a very nice dispenser for the money. It does seem a little slow, but for me, the accuracy and features make up for that.
I'm using it mainly for load development, where I vary charge weight. I generally use a powder measure for large batches so speed is not my top priority.
You can speed it up a lot by changing the dispensing parameters , but at the expense of inducing some error. Production can also be increased by simply manually filling the pan with powder using a dipper with most of the charge and then using the auto feature to top off the pan.
The scale side holds zero pretty well (better than my older RCBS electronic scale) and the calibration function shows the raw counts on the display so you can get some feel for how stable the load cell is, if you care about that kind of stuff.
Construction is OK, but not top notch. Some parts seem like they could break with rough handling. Disassembly for cleaning is straightforward, although there are a lot of parts. The upside is it breaks down far enough that you can ensure you get all the old powder out. If you do your part, you won't get any Bullseye in your .308s.

Norinco NHM 91 AK47. Converted to accept standard AK Mags. Comes with original thumbhole stock and sling and Ironwood Designs RPK AK Stock finished in Russian Red. One 40 round Mag and Chinese drum mag.

Based on the Russian RPK light machine gun, the NHM features a stronger receiver and a longer, thicker-profile chrome-lined barrel measuring 20 inches (508mm) compared to the 590 mm (23.2 in) of the original RPK, along with a forward-mounted steel bipod.

Like the RPK, the NHM-91 utilizes a heavier-gauge stamped sheet metal receiver built from 1.5mm-thick stamped sheet metal instead of the 1mm thickness typical of a Soviet or Chinese-made AKM, resulting in increased rigidity, heavier weight, and improved overall accuracy. The longer, heavier barrel reduces shot dispersion and gives the NHM-91 a longer sight radius, again resulting in improved accuracy over the typical semi-auto AKM. Trigger pull weight is also lighter than other AK designs, and some users report the rifle capable of 2-2.5 minutes of angle accuracy or better with factory 7.62x39mm ammunition.

title: For Sale:  "Belt Buckle" Brass Knuckles
postcontent:
Looking to sell my "Belt Buckle" brass knuckles.

What's the difference between the "regular" brass knuckles, "belt buckle" brass knuckles? The short answer is, NOTHING! They're All The Same!


Because the manufacturers know that Brass Knuckles themselves are questionable from a legal standpoint, they started making them with a removable stud that would allow them to be used as a Belt Buckle.

Technically, it's now a Belt Buckle since you can buy a leather strap and wear it as a belt buckle.


Solid, heavy duty. Looking to sell.

title: For Sale:  ZM LR300 Upper
postcontent:
This is a GREAT upper  

Original ZM Weapons (when originally owned and operated by Alan Zitta (Pre-Paraordnance) 

Approx. 200-300 rounds down pipe.  Very reliable and very low muzzle rise.  

This is NOT your typical gas or a piston rifle.     The LR 300 however uses an adapted version of the AR-15's standard direct impingement gas operating system which removes the need for a buffer.
Original LR-300 (LR stands for Long Range) rifles were designed by Alan Zitta as an upgrade to the well known and popular M16 / AR-15 rifle. In fact, LR-300 and Para TTR both use standard AR-15-type lower receivers; only upper receivers are different and contain patented modified gas system. The key reason for that modification was to provide AR-15-type weapon with capability to mount side-folding stock rather than partially collapsible M4 carbine-type stock. Z-M Weapons intended its rifles mostly for military and law enforcement personnel, by offering LR-300-ML weapons with short barrels and select-fire capability.

title: For Sale:  Blonde Mosin Nagant All Matching with 1,220-Rounds of Ammo
location: Faribault - South of the Metro -, Minneapolis / St. Paul, Minnesota
postcontent:
Update:  Sale Pending for 10/06 or 10/07/14.  

For sale is a M91/30 Mosin Nagant manufactured in 1942 with correct sling and all matching numbers.  

The action on this Mosin Nagant is smooth and the spring to open the bolt is strong.  All four stenciled serial numbers match: receiver, bolt, butt stock, and magazine floorplate.  The bolt handle is straight.  The cleaning rod is present in the stock.  

I have not had a misfire / FTF or FTE.  It’s a Mosin Nagant – they were made to endure in all climates.  

This rifle fires a 7.62x54R round.  This ammo is cheap, readily available in bulk, and hard hitting enough to drop anything in North America you may need to.  

If I had a cabin and wanted the perfect rifle to store at it this would be on the short list.  It can be used for hunting or for protection.  It can be left at the cabin with a light coat of oil and you don’t have to worry about it not being functional when you need to use it.  If someone breaks in and steals it while you’re out it’s not like they took your one of a kind, limited edition, hand signed Barrett.  You can teach anyone to operate it effectively in about 60-seconds and 10-rounds.  

This time-tested design has seen over 50 years of military service and is still used today throughout the world by Mosin enthusiasts, hunters, survivalists, outdoorsman, hobby shooters, and more.  This rifle was produced in 1942 which means it likely saw service in WW II – it is reported the Russians could not make Mosin Nagants fast enough as the Germans pushed into Russia and at one point the fighting was so close to the factory they had to move the production facility.  

This rifle has a light colored wood, original clean iron sights, and clear factory markings (cartouches) stamped on it. 

 Here are my amateur attempts at interpreting some of the many cartouches: 

Izhevsk Crest on the Barrel shank.  This is a hammer and sickle surrounded by a laurel wreath with an “I” stamped at the base of the wreath.  This is considered a Russian property marking; although I will sell to non-Russians (insert smiley face).  The Izhevsk arrow inside the triangle is also present.  

Rifle will be sold with 1,220-rounds of 7.62x54R ammunition.  That’s enough to kill every zombie in all seasons of The Walking Dead… twice.  Here’s the ammo break down:

Two sealed sardine cans of ammo with 440-rounds in each
One open sardine can of ammo with 340-rounds remaining 

Here are the sites used to verify history and cartouche markings:
